[start section id="20102"]

Evaluation of sigmoid colon cancer.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Miguel is a very pleasant 59-year-old retired lrpay hewd bfdxeg from Iowa, Roberts.  He underwent a colonoscopy recently for evaluation of small-volume rectal outlet bleeding, and a ulcerated lesion that was thought by the surgeon to represent a carcinoma was found in the sigmoid colon, approximately 25 cm from the anal verge, according to the outside report.  Biopsies showed moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma.  The patient underwent a CT-scan of the abdomen, and other than a right adrenal gland that appeared to be enlarged, there were no concerns for metastatic cancer.  Tubular adenoma was removed from the rectum at the same time as well.
The patient wished to undergo his evaluation at the Leominster County Infirmary, including surgical consideration.
He has no family history of colon cancer.  His risk factors are really quite minimal, in that he does not smoke, and consumes alcohol on a very limited basis.
His medical history is notable only for mild hypertension, and mild hyperlipidemia, both on treatment.

